            </div>

            <div class="faq-grid">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question">Can one rep really be enough to build muscle?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>Yes. Muscle growth is stimulated by time under tension and mechanical load, not the number of repetitions. A 90-second one-rep set provides three times more time under tension than a conventional 10-rep set lasting 30 seconds. The research on this is clear: 60-90 seconds of time under tension is effective for hypertrophy. You're getting that stimulus with one focused movement instead of multiple reps where fatigue progressively compromises your form.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question">Why emphasize the negative so much (70 of 90 seconds)?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>Your muscles can handle approximately 40% more load during the eccentric (lowering) phase than the concentric (lifting) phase. A meta-analysis published in the British Journal of Sports Medicine found that eccentric-emphasized training produced up to 50% greater strength gains than conventional training. The 30-20-40 protocol puts 70 of its 90 seconds in the negative phases, maximizing this effect. The extended final 40-second negative takes the muscle to complete fatigue in the safest possible way—slowly and under control.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question">What weight should I use?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>Start with about 50-60% of what you'd normally use for 10 conventional reps. The extended time makes this weight brutally challenging. If you can't maintain smooth, controlled movement for all 90 seconds, the weight is too heavy. It's better to start too light and increase next session than to start too heavy and compromise the protocol. When you can consistently hit 30-20-40 with smooth movement, add 5-10% and work back up.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question">This seems too simple. What's the catch?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>Try it and you'll find the catch: it's incredibly demanding. That 20-second lifting phase—trying to lift the weight when your muscles are already fatigued from 30 seconds of lowering—is one of the hardest things you'll do in a gym. The simplicity is in the structure, not the effort. Most people who dismiss one-rep training haven't actually tried to maintain a true 30-20-40 with an appropriate weight. It requires complete focus, significant mental fortitude, and genuine muscular effort.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question">Why machines instead of free weights?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>During a 90-second rep, your muscles experience profound fatigue. With free weights, this fatigue can lead to dropped weights or loss of balance—especially during a 40-second lowering phase when your muscles are giving out. Machines provide the stability and safety net needed for this kind of training. Nautilus machines in particular were designed by Arthur Jones specifically to provide optimal resistance through the full range of motion, with cam systems that accentuate the negative phase. The machine catches the weight if you fail, so you can push to true muscular fatigue safely.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question">Is this safe for people over 50 or with joint issues?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>This method is arguably the safest form of strength training available. Every repetition creates opportunities for injury—at the turnaround points, during fatigue-induced form breakdown, when momentum generates impact forces. By reducing your workout to 8 slow, controlled movements, you eliminate almost all of these risks. The continuous, smooth motion puts no impact stress on joints. Many people with knee, shoulder, or back issues find this allows them to strength train effectively when conventional methods caused pain. That said, always consult your physician before starting any new exercise program.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question">How do I progress over time?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>Progress is measured by your ability to hit target times with increasing weight. When you can consistently complete a true 30-20-40 on all exercises for 2-3 workouts in a row, add 5-10% weight. Your times will drop initially with the new weight—that's expected. Work back up to full target times, then increase again. Keep detailed records of weights and actual times achieved.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question">How often should I train?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer">
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>Twice per week with at least 3 days between sessions. Because each rep involves 90 seconds of intense muscle tension, recovery demands are significant. Training more frequently doesn't produce better results—it often produces worse results by not allowing complete recovery. Each session takes about 30 minutes, so you're investing roughly one hour per week in strength training. That's enough for excellent results when the intensity is appropriate.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
